# Codebase documentation

`docs/src/docs/codebase/**` owns memory design, design scope, implementation style, testing and validation.

`docs/language-overview.md` remains the complete compiler-facing language
authority during the language documentation migration.

`docs/src/docs/codebase/language/overview.bd` indexes focused Beandown
replacement references as they are prepared and reviewed against that
authority.

Use the progress matrix for current support. Use the roadmap for sequencing and unaccepted proposals.

## Core reading

- `docs/src/docs/codebase/style-guide/style-guide.bd`
- `docs/src/docs/codebase/memory-management/overview.bd`

Read `docs/src/docs/codebase/style-guide/validation.bd` before completing or
reviewing a non-trivial change.

Read `docs/src/docs/codebase/style-guide/testing.bd` when work changes
behaviour, diagnostics, compiler stages, backends, tests or fixtures.

For compiler architecture and stage ownership, use
`docs/compiler-design-overview.md`, the canonical technical design reference.

For design-boundary questions, read
`docs/src/docs/codebase/design-scope/overview.bd`.

## Compiler flow

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    project files
        -> Stage 0: canonical project graph and source ownership
        -> Stage 1: tokenization
        -> Stage 2: header parsing
        -> Stage 3: dependency sorting
        -> Stage 4: AST construction
        -> Stage 5: HIR generation
        -> Stage 6: borrow validation
        -> Stage 7: project assembly and backend lowering
        -> output files
]

## Core architectural rules

- User-facing source, syntax, import, type, rule, borrow, config and deferred-feature failures use `CompilerDiagnostic`. `CompilerError` is for internal compiler, filesystem, backend, dev-server and tooling failures.
- Stage 0 builds one canonical module graph, assigns file ownership and compiles each module once in dependency order.
- Each module owns one local `TypeEnvironment`. Use local `TypeId` equality for module-local decisions and canonical project identities across module interfaces.
- Header parsing owns top-level declaration discovery and declaration shells. AST consumes sorted headers and header-built visibility.
- Import preparation builds the visibility environment used by dependency sorting and AST. Expression and type resolution use the active `ScopeContext`.
- Generics, traits and explicit cast evidence resolve before HIR.
- AST owns template composition, constant folding, slot routing, runtime handoff preparation and compile-time page fragment metadata. TIR remains AST-local.
- HIR is the first backend-facing semantic IR. It makes control flow and cross-module call targets explicit.
- Borrow validation reads HIR and writes side-table facts. It doesn't mutate HIR or decide final runtime ownership.
- GC is the semantic baseline. Ownership and deterministic destruction are optimisation layers.
- Existing values use shared, read-only access by default. Copies are explicit, `~` requests exclusive access and ownership transfer remains compiler-inferred.
- Backend builders consume the compiled project graph, entry or package link plans, validated module HIR, paired type environments and borrow facts. They don't rediscover source imports or reinterpret source syntax.

## Design in one minute

- Keep the source language small, explicit and statically inspectable.
- Prefer constrained mechanisms over general metaprogramming.
- Prefer static reuse through generics and trait bounds.
- Use choices for runtime heterogeneity.
- Keep ownership and backend optimisation behind stable source semantics.
- Distinguish unimplemented design from intentionally excluded design.

See `docs/src/docs/codebase/design-scope/overview.bd` for the high-level rationale and `docs/compiler-design-overview.md` for concrete compiler architecture.
